There is no way to purchase all of the available tables in one shot.  I don't care if they want me to pay full retail.  A dollar is fair for a well developed table.  But don't make me go through the painful purchase process for each individual table.  That, more than cost, has prevented me from purchasing more tables.
replyContent:
Thanks for the feedback, Michael. 

Some Android devices have an accessibility feature called magnification gestures, which can cause the app to lag. You can disable it in your device's settings:  Settings > Accessibility > Vision> Magnification gestures. Please let us know if that doesn't resolve the issue.

I don't play a lot of pinball games on my Note 2. Some things don't translate to screens. (Like Jenga)This app is repetitive, difficult to grasp the current objective, and frustratingly easy to lose through no fault of your own. First, the repetition comes when you realize there is one table and one way to play that table. Then, the first shot from the lightsaber launcher does exactly what it always does, NO variation on the "kickoff"? Very rare for a pinball game, real or app. Next, what am I supposed to be aiming for? How do I know that? The lights are flashing everywhere, the tiny monotone scoreboard (WHY?!) tells you to do something, but it's hard to read and hard to understand.Example, Scene 1: Get the lightsaber. Um, HOW? Mini-game with the floating practice blaster, HOW? Jackpots: HOW? So frustrating to not know if you're aiming for the correct path/object. Finally, the ball goes to the far left or right side of the table and down past the flippers way too often. If I perfectly time my shot and it bounces 6 times and then I get to watch it slip down the LANDO path and I lose the game, it's not MY fault and I can't do anything to win. Keep working to improve gameplay. Please!

I've got all three tables and really am impressed. The artwork and animations are gorgeous and the gameplay and many goals are well implemented. I only observe two problems,  neither a dealbreaker:  The feel is just a wee bit stiff. Not to disparage your app, but Pinball Arcade has a more solidly realistic feel to me, though as one with zero design experience I can't say precisely why. I do think there's some wiggle room for optimization. 'Episode V' runs smoothly most of the time, but 'Boba Fett' occasionally has some annoying choppiness to it and 'Clones' suffers more frequently from these annoying hesitations as the data flow chokes up. I just don't think that should be happening on my nearly new Tegra 3 powered Asus Infinity tablet.  I'm definitely happy to play this daily, but I gotta deduct one star for the intermittent choppy performance with two of the three tables. If you can optimize it to eliminate those freezups it's easily a five star game...and if you can make the physics more believable It'll be a rave review!
